rivetrunner.py
==============

About
-----

`rivetrunner.py` is a script that runs
link:http://projects.hepforge.org/rivet/[`rivetgun`] multiple time with
different parameter settings and stores the output in a way professor can use
for running the Monte Carlo tuning.


Usage
-----

To run `rivetrunner.py` call

--------------------
 rivetrunner.py [options]
--------------------

Currently the supported options are:

`-V, \--verbose`::
    print status messages

`-D, \--debug`::
    print debug (very verbose) messages

`-Q, \--quiet`::
    be very quiet (overrides verbose and debug)

`-r, \--run`::
    actually call Rivet rather than just writing out the command

`-g <GENERATOR>, \--gen=<GENERATOR>`::
    generator to use (Rivet name convention)

`-a <ANALYSES>, \--analysis=<ANALYSES>`::
    add a Rivet analysis (can be used multiple times)

`-A, \--all-analyses`::
    add all Rivet analyses, as for the rivetgun `-A` option

`-P <RIVET_PARAM_FILES>, \--rivet-paramfile=<RIVET_PARAM_FILES>`::
    specify a Rivet parameter file as passed to rivetgun with `-P`
    (can be used multiple times)

`-R, \--fake-reference`::
    make an extra run as a fake reference point

`\--ref-range=<REFRANGE>`::
    specify central fraction of the param range from which to sample the fake
    reference

`-p <PARAMSFILE>, \--params=<PARAMSFILE>`::
    file containing the parameter names and sample ranges

`-n <NUM_EVENTS_PER_RUN>, \--num-events=<NUM_EVENTS_PER_RUN>`::
    how many events to generate in each run

`-N <NUM_RUNS>, \--num-runs=<NUM_RUNS>`::
    how many parameter space points to run the generator for

`\--first-run=<NUM_FIRST_RUN>`::
    number given to the first run

`\--nice=<NICE>`::
    optional nice level

`-o <OUT_DIR>, \--outdir=<OUT_DIR>`::
    directory into which to write the generator output

`-b <BATCH_SYSTEM>, \--batch=<BATCH_SYSTEM>`::
    use a batch submission system. Choose from `NO`, `PBS`.
    *NOT IMPLEMENTED!*

`-T <NUM_THREADS>, \--threads=<NUM_THREADS>`::
    max number of threads to be used (default is 1)

`-t, \--timestamp`::
    add a timestamp prefix to the output directory name


Parameter File
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The parameter file passed using `\--params` option specifies which parameters
should be varied and within what range. Lines starting with `#` and empty lines
are ignored.

Each line defines a parameter and the corresponding range in the following
format, the fields are separated by whitespace:

--------------------
<parametername>   <loweredge>   <upperedge>
--------------------

Parameter files specified with the `\--rivet-paramfile` are used additionally.


